[[File:A Brixham trawler.jpg|thumb|Painting of ''A Brixham trawler'' by [[William Adolphus Knell]]. The painting is now in the [[National Maritime Museum]].]]
[[File:Jib and staysail of Leader.jpg|thumb|Looking forward on the deck of the Brixham trawler ''Leader'', under way under sail off the south coast of England. July 2008.]]
[[File:Leader at anchor.jpg|thumb|The Brixham trawler ''Leader'' at anchor off Cawsand, near Plymouth. July 2008.]]

A '''Brixham trawler''' is a type of wooden, deep-sea [[fishing trawler]] first built in [[Brixham]] in Devon, England, in the 19th century<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.rmg.co.uk/collections/objects/12718.html|title=A Brixham trawler - National Maritime Museum|publisher=[[National Maritime Museum|Royal Museums Greenwich]]|accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref> and known for its high speed.<ref name="TS">{{cite web|url=http://www.trinitysailing.org/vessels/brixham-trawler/|title=Brixham deep sea trawlers|accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref> The design was copied by [[boat builder]]s around Britain, and some were sold to fishermen in other countries on the [[North Sea]].<ref name="TS" />

The Brixham trawler was a heavy displacement boat of some 60–80&nbsp;ft length on the deck, with a long straight keel, a straight vertical stem, usually a fantail stern, and a low freeboard to ease the handling of the nets, though this feature was disguised by high bulwarks.<ref name="Tiller Press">{{cite book|last1=Marchaj|first1=Czesław|title=Seaworthiness, the forgotten factor|date=1996|publisher=Tiller Press|location=St Michaels, MD|isbn=1-888671-09-2|page=18|edition=Revised}}</ref>  Brixham trawlers carried a tall [[gaff rig]], often [[ketch|ketch rigged]] though also simply a large [[sloop]], that was powerful enough to carry them quickly to and from the fishing grounds and to tow large [[trawling|trawls.]]<ref name="Brixham Trawlers">{{cite web|last1=Trinity Sailing Foundation|title=Brixham Trawlers|url=http://www.trinitysailing.org/vessels/brixham-trawler/|website=Trinity Sailing|publisher=rinity Sailing Foundation|accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>  Renowned yacht aerodynamicist and sailor [[Czesław Marchaj|C. A. Marchaj]] commented on the type, "With little area of keel surface, these boats lacked weatherliness as compared with the [[Falmouth Quay Punt|Quay Punt]]… Not without reason, fishermen of the north-east coast swore that the forefoot took them to windward."<ref name="Tiller Press"/>

Brixham once had a fleet of 400 such vessels,<ref name="KJH">{{cite web|url=http://www.kjappeal.org/history.html|title=Kenya Jacaranda History|accessdate=7 February 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202015738/http://kjappeal.org/history.html|archivedate=2 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> whose distinctive red sails were coated with local [[red ochre]] for protection. Other fleets were at Lowestoft with 375 trawlers, 450 at Hull, 625 at Great Yarmouth and 840 at Grimsby, with smaller numbers at other places.<ref name="Brixham Trawlers"/>  Only five remain afloat. One of them, ''Provident (BM28)'', took part in the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]].<ref name=List>Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant, ''List of vessels taking part''</ref>

== Rescue ==
On 1 January 1915 the crew of ''Provident BM291'' rescued 71 sailors from {{HMS|Formidable|1898|6}}, torpedoed and sunk by a German submarine in the English Channel during the night in a gale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warandsecurity.com/2015/02/03/the-sinking-of-hms-formidable-1-january-1915/|title=The Sinking of HMS Formidable 1 January 1915|last=|first=|date=|website=War and Security|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>

