{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox building | name = Vincenti Tower | native_name = Torri Vinċenti | native_name_lang = mt | image = It-Torri Vincenti.jpg | image_caption = View of the Vincenti Tower | coordinates = {{coord|35|50|51.9|N|14|28|5.2|E|display=inline}} | status = Partially intact | building_type = [[Fortified house|Fortified]] [[tower]] | location = [[Mqabba]], [[Malta]] | namesake = Fra Orfeo de Vincenzo | completion_date = 1726 | demolition_date = 1940s (partially) | owner = Private | material = [[Limestone]] | floor_count = 4 }}
'''Vincenti Tower''' ({{lang-mt|Torri Vinċenti}}) is a [[tower]] in [[Mqabba]], [[Malta]]. It was built in 1726 by Fra Orfeo de Vincenzo, a Prior of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St. John]]. It forms part of a countryside residence, which also includes a palace/farmhouse known as ''Ta' Torri Spero'', and a garden between the palace and the tower.<ref name="southwestmalta">{{cite web|date=10 April 1996|first=Carmen|last=Lia|title=Imqabba: The Tower of Vincenti|url=http://southwestmalta.info/VillagesSub/villages/mqabba.html|website=southwestmalta.info|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621133002/http://southwestmalta.info/VillagesSub/villages/mqabba.html|archivedate=21 June 2016}}</ref>
The tower was originally four stories high, with a balcony on its second floor, and it had a scarped base which made it somewhat similar to coastal watchtowers such as the [[De Redin towers]]. The tower had a coat of arms and a inscription commemorating its construction, but these are now lost.<ref name="southwestmalta"/>
On 2 June 1941, during [[World War II]], the British military requisitioned the tower from its owner Sir William John England, and used it as an Observation Post. It was prone to aerial bombardment due to its proximity to the [[RAF Luqa]] airfield. It was hit on 12 April 1942, and the bottom floor was damaged although the structure did not collapse.<ref name="southwestmalta"/>
However, the [[Royal Air Force]] later decided to pull down the tower since it was deemed dangerous to the nearby airfield. The upper sections were pulled down, but the scarped ground floor and part of the first floor were retained.<ref name="southwestmalta"/>
[[File:Ta Torri Spero.jpeg|thumb|left|Ta' Torri Spero, a country residence which was built at the same time as the tower]]
Today, the remains of the tower as well as the nearby garden and farmhouse are private property.<ref>{{cite web|title=Farmhouse in Mqabba|url=http://www.doorsrealestate.com/property/012950S/farmhouse-in-mqabba/|website=Doors Real Estate Services|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621132723/http://www.doorsrealestate.com/property/012950S/farmhouse-in-mqabba/|archivedate=21 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ta Torri – Has Washer|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/VacationRentalReview-g1906054-d1918997-Ta_Torri-Mqabba_Island_of_Malta.html|website=[[TripAdvisor]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311093344/http://www.tripadvisor.com/VacationRentalReview-g1906054-d1918997-Ta_Torri-Mqabba_Island_of_Malta.html|archivedate=11 March 2016}}</ref> The tower was included on the Antiquities List of 1925 as "the old tower",<ref>{{cite web|title=Protection of Antiquities Regulations 21st November, 1932 Government Notice 402 of 1932, as Amended by Government Notices 127 of 1935 and 338 of 1939.|url=https://www.mepa.org.mt/file.aspx?f=2627|website=[[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6guMwmZDW?url=https://www.mepa.org.mt/file.aspx?f=2627|archivedate=20 April 2016|access-date=10 February 2016|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and it was scheduled as a Grade 1 monument by the [[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=L-Istorja tal-Imqabba|url=http://www.mqabba.gov.mt/?m=content&id=263|website=Mqabba Local Council|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122214347/http://www.mqabba.gov.mt/?m=content&id=263|archivedate=22 November 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref> It is also listed on the [[National Inventory of the Cultural Property of the Maltese Islands]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Torre Vincenti|url=http://www.culturalheritage.gov.mt/filebank/inventory/Knights%20Fortifications/1442.pdf|website=National Inventory of the Cultural Property of the Maltese Islands|date=28 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123081246/http://www.culturalheritage.gov.mt/filebank/inventory/Knights%20Fortifications/1442.pdf|archivedate=23 November 2015}}</ref> {{clear}} ==References== {{reflist}}
